<subSubSection id="C3266566AE4EFFA1FF0114064749FAB4" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8336EDAE4EFFA1FF01140647BEFAEC" blockId="42.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FF011406430EFBB8" bold="true" box="[199,308,1087,1113]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species possesses a metathoracic ostiolar canal that is weakly raised above evaporative areas, the ostiolar peritreme is oval and moderately raised (as in 
<figureCitation id="13072A68AE4EFFA1FCF7145A41A9FB9F" box="[817,915,1123,1150]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetId="figure-15@31.[151,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 10. Scanning electron micrographs. a. Pronotum (left lateral view); b–h. Thoracic pleura; i–m. Metatarsus. n, o. Pretarsal claw. a. Valdasus schoechnerri; b. Amapacylapus amapariensis; c, i. Cylapus tenuicornis; d. Peltidocylapus scutellaris; e, j. Valdasus henryi; f. Bothriomiris dissimulans; g. Cylapocoris sp.; h. Psallops sp.; k, o. Vannius sp.; l. Fulvius sp.; m. Cylapocoris sp.; n. Cylapinus minusculus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5760414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5760414/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 10d</figureCitation>
), and the tarsus with tarsomere I is two times shorter than II and III combined (as in 
<figureCitation id="13072A68AE4EFFA1FD8814BE40F3FB40" box="[590,713,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,181,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-27@32.[169,1418,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 11. Scanning electron micrographs. a, e, g, m. Dorsal habitus; b, n. Lateral habitus; h, l. Scutellum; c, f, i. Thoracic pleura; d, j, o. Tarsus. k. Pretarsal claw. a–d. Cylapinus minusculus; e, f. Cylapoides unicolor; g–j. Peltidocylapus caudatus; k. Peltidocylapus calyciformis; l. Peltidocylapus ecuadorensis; m–o. Peltidocylapus scutellaris." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5760418" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5760418/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Figs 11j, o</figureCitation>
). These characters do not fit the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FB0D14BE471DFB40" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1832" box="[1227,1319,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FB0D14BE471DFB40" box="[1227,1319,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Cylapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where the ostiolar canal is strongly raised, the peritreme is arcuate and sharply pointed (
<figureCitation id="13072A68AE4EFFA1FBCE1492465DFB24" box="[1032,1127,1195,1221]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetId="figure-15@31.[151,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 10. Scanning electron micrographs. a. Pronotum (left lateral view); b–h. Thoracic pleura; i–m. Metatarsus. n, o. Pretarsal claw. a. Valdasus schoechnerri; b. Amapacylapus amapariensis; c, i. Cylapus tenuicornis; d. Peltidocylapus scutellaris; e, j. Valdasus henryi; f. Bothriomiris dissimulans; g. Cylapocoris sp.; h. Psallops sp.; k, o. Vannius sp.; l. Fulvius sp.; m. Cylapocoris sp.; n. Cylapinus minusculus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5760414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5760414/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 10c</figureCitation>
) and tarsomere I is as long or longer than II and III tarsomeres combined. The combination of these characters is found in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FA8414F642D7FAEC" authorityName=": Carvalho &amp; Fontes" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FA8414F642D7FAEC" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Peltidocylapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as defined in the present paper, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FD4314CA4178FAEC" authorityName=": Carvalho &amp; Fontes" authorityYear="1968" box="[645,834,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="festinabundus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FD4314CA4178FAEC" box="[645,834,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. festinabundus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here transferred from 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FB9114CA4689FAEC" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1832" box="[1111,1203,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FB9114CA4689FAEC" box="[1111,1203,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Cylapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FB1114CA4747FAEC" authorityName=": Carvalho &amp; Fontes" authorityYear="1968" box="[1239,1405,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FB1114CA4747FAEC" box="[1239,1405,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Peltidocylapus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8336EDAE4EFFA1FF01152E4749FAB4" blockId="42.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FF01152E4344FAD0" authorityName=": Carvalho &amp; Fontes" authorityYear="1968" box="[199,382,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="festinabundus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FF01152E4344FAD0" box="[199,382,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P. festinabundus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is like 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FE0B152E406EFAD0" authorityName=": Carvalho &amp; Fontes" authorityYear="1968" box="[461,596,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerbereus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FE0B152E406EFAD0" box="[461,596,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P. cerbereus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FDA4152E40F5FAD0" baseAuthorityName="Distant" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[610,719,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nubilus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FDA4152E40F5FAD0" box="[610,719,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P. nubilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D6EAE4EFFA1FCCD152E414DFAD1" baseAuthorityName="Distant" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[779,887,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Peltidocylapus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picatus">
<emphasis id="B948EAFFAE4EFFA1FCCD152E414DFAD1" box="[779,887,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">P. picatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in sharing indistinct, weakly convex longitudinal medial swelling on scutellum. It can be distinguished by the yellow, large patch on lateral portion of pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
